[2]
Date: 18 Apr 2003
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Singapore - Ministry of Health [edited]
<http://app.moh.gov.sg/sar/sar0301.asp?id=1&mid=6240>


As of 18 Apr 2003, 2 additional SARS patients have been discharged,
bringing the total number of patients who have recovered from SARS to
97. 59 SARS patients remain hospitalised.

One additional SARS case was reported today. She is the wife of a
probable SARS case who had been previously admitted to [Tan Tock Seng
Hospital] TTSH as a suspect case. Her husband had visited the
Radiology Department at [Singapore General Hospital] SGH on 1 Apr
2003 and later developed clinical signs consistent with SARS.

Situation Update at SGH
So far, 62 persons are linked to the SGH cluster, comprising 25 SGH
staff, 20 inpatients, and 17 contacts. 48 are probable cases.

Precautionary measures for SGH Ward 74
SGH had moved all patients who had been through Wards 57 & 58 to TTSH
on 6-7 Apr 2003. A patient who was previously in Ward 57 between 26
and 28 Mar 2003, and subsequently transferred to Ward 74 between 28
Mar 2003 and 6 Apr 2003 for neurological management, was later
transferred to TTSH on 7 Apr 2003. In view of this, Ward 74 was
placed on close surveillance. On 9 and 10 Apr 2003, 3 nurses from
Ward 74 B2 station (Neurology ward) were noted to have low-grade
fever (37.6 degrees C). They were given medical leave. 2 of them were
admitted to our Isolation Ward for observation. All 3 of them became
afebrile after 1 day and were sent home with further medical leave.

On 14 Apr 2003, one of the medical officers in the Neurology unit
also reported sick with a low-grade fever for a day. He was put on
medical leave. On 14 Apr 2003, SGH noted that there were 3 patients
in one cubicle in Ward 74 who had fever. However, these were patients
who had had fever intermittently for some time, in part due to the
nature of their underlying illnesses. As a precaution, we transferred
all 6 patients in that cubicle to our Isolation Ward on the same day
(14 Apr 2003). One of these 3 patients was admitted on 27 Mar 2003
with a fever. He was diagnosed with pneumonia on 29 Mar 2003, treated
with antibiotics and improved. However, on 17 Apr 2003, he became
chesty and breathless. On 17 Apr 2003 evening, as a further
precaution, a decision was made to transfer all 3 patients to TTSH.
They have been classified as suspect cases.

As a further precaution, the 3 Ward 74 nurses have also been recalled
to be re-evaluated in TTSH today. SGH will also move all 55 patients
of Ward 74 to TTSH starting tonight (17 Apr 2003). The neurologists
at TTSH, who are part of the [National Neuroscience Institute] NNI,
will look after these patients. The clinical management of these
patients will not be disrupted. 2 neurologists have been assigned to
handle communication issues with the patients' relatives. One will be
stationed at SGH and the other at TTSH to update patients' relatives
on the transfer of patients and the management of their medical
condition at TTSH. This is to ensure a smooth transfer of patients to
TTSH.

SGH's clinical departments started working on a modular system on 10
Apr 2003. Each team is mapped to a fixed location (such as a part of
a ward or an outpatient clinic). With this mapping of persons to
place, the risk of exposure is reduced. As such, SGH's neurology
outpatient service can still continue to function while the inpatient
neurology doctors are put on Hospital Enforced Quarantine. 2 of the
neurologists from the outpatient service team will now be deployed to
cover the inpatient area.

As a precaution, some 100 staff from this latest development in Ward
74 will be put on Hospital Enforced Quarantine. Active contact
tracing of patients, visitors, and staff of Ward 74 is in progress.
Visitors to Ward 74 after 26 Mar 2003 to date should monitor their
temperature.

These strong precautionary measures are in line with SGH's intention
to do everything possible to deal with the SARS outbreak.

Added Precautions in Public Hospitals
Starting today, all public hospitals will restrict visitors to one
per patient per day. This is an added precaution to reduce the risk
of the virus spread.

A summary of the SARS cases to date:
There was one additional death today, bringing the total deaths to 16
(of which 2 are pending further post mortem test results). This was
the [National University Hospital] NUH inpatient who was in contact
with a previous NUH SARS case.

Discharged: 97
Hospitalised: 59 (including 17 in intensive care)
Deaths: 14 + 2 (pending further post mortem test results)
Total: 172

Suspected: 80 (including 5 children below 18)
Under home quarantine orders: 444

--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

