[3]
Date: 18 Apr 2003
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Health Canada [edited]
<http://www.hc-sc.gc.ca/pphb-dgspsp/sars-sras/eu-ae/sars20030418_e.html>


Summary of Severe Acute Respiratory Syndrome (SARS) Cases: 18 Apr 2003

Since yesterday, no additional probable cases of SARS have been
reported in Canada. A total of 132 individuals who meet the probable
case definition and 172 who meet the suspect case definition of SARS
have been reported, including 13 deaths. In addition to British
Columbia and Ontario, which are reporting probable cases, Alberta,
Saskatchewan, New Brunswick, and Prince Edward Island are also
reporting suspect cases of SARS (Table 1).

At the present time, the case fatality rate in Canada is estimated at
approximately 4.3 percent of probable or suspect cases (13 of 304
probable or suspect cases). Most of the case fatalities occurred in
patients with underlying illness, and nearly all were elderly
patients over the age of 70 years.

Table 1: Cumulative Number of SARS Cases Reported in Canada: 18 Apr 2003

Province/Territory: Individuals meeting the criteria for probable
case (1)/ suspected case (1)/ deaths

British Columbia: 4/ 41/ 0
Alberta: 0/ 5/ 0
Saskatchewan: 0/ 1/ 0
Ontario: 128/ 119/ 13 (2)
New Brunswick: 0/ 2/ 0
Prince Edward Island: 0/ 4/ 0

Total: 132/ 172/ 13
(1)These persons may be excluded the probable or suspect case list if
another cause is identified to fully explain their illness
(2) 12 of 13 deaths were in probable cases, and one of the 13 deaths
was recently re-classified as a suspect case.

A summary of the current status of probable cases of SARS in Canada
as of 18 Apr 2003 is presented in Table 2. 54 individuals have been
discharged (41.5 percent) and of the 64 individuals currently
hospitalised, 41 (64.1 percent) are improving or in stable condition.
In addition, nearly all of the suspect cases reported in Ontario,
British Columbia, Alberta, Saskatchewan, New Brunswick, and Prince
Edward Island have either recovered or are presently recovering.

Table 2: Currently known reported status of probable cases of SARS in
Canada: 18 Apr 2003
(N=130, excludes 2 for whom status is unknown)

Current Status: Number/ probable cases (percent)
Hospitalised: 64/130 (49.2 percent)
Improving 14/64 (21.9 percent)
Stable 27/64 (42.2 percent)
Critical/Deteriorating 13/64 (20.3 percent)
Unknown 10/64 (15.6 percent)
Discharged(1) 54/130 (41.5 percent)
Deceased 122/130 (9.2 percent)
Total no. probable cases for whom current status is known: 130 (100 percent)

(1) includes cases who have either recovered or are recovering
(2) 1 death not accounted for in this table, has recently been
re-classified as a suspect case

The current evidence suggests that respiratory droplet transmission,
requiring close contact with a case of SARS, is the predominant mode
of transmission. In the province of Ontario, the majority of cases
have been associated with specific transmission settings, such as
household, hospital, and specific community groups or settings. There
are currently 30 cases reported amongst approximately 500 members of
a religious group in Toronto. The index case of this community
cluster is linked to the first hospital cluster. The disease spread
to a total of 14 members of the index case's extended family as well
as to other members of the religious group. The key transmission
settings include a gathering held on 28--29 Mar 2003, the funeral
visitation for the index case held on 3 Apr 2003, and other social
gatherings during and after these dates. Local health authorities
have implemented isolation of all contacts of suspect and probable
cases, including all 500 members of the religious group, in an effort
to contain any further spread within and outside of this social
network. Case finding and contact tracing efforts in the group are
continuing.

Travellers who have returned from an affected area in Asia and their
close contacts account for the remaining cases in Ontario and the
other provinces. The number of probable cases by reported symptom
onset date and type of exposure (where known) is provided in (Figure
1) [see webpage
<http://www.hc-sc.gc.ca/pphb-dgspsp/sars-sras/eu-ae/sars20030418_e.html>
for epidemic curve by type of exposure - Mod.MPP]

