[B]
Date: 18 Apr 2003
From: Susan Rossmann <srossman@giveblood.org>

Subject: FDA issues guidance on blood collection regarding SARS

On their website <http://www.fda.gov/cber/gdlns/sarsbld.htm>
and the associated Talk Paper
<http://www.fda.gov/bbs/topics/ANSWERS/2003/ANS01215.html>

The recommendation is to ask donors whether they have had SARS or
suspected SARS in the last 28 days, whether they have had close
contact with a person with SARS or suspected SARS in the last 14
days, and whether they have travelled to an area with SARS in the
last 14 days (using the geographic areas in the CDC case definition,
to be modified as the CDC updates).

--
Susan N. Rossmann, M.D., Ph.D, Medical Director
Gulf Coast Regional Blood Center
1400 La Concha Dr, Houston TX 77054
<srossman@giveblood.org>

[Full details on the proposed position paper with recommendations for
blood banks can be found at:
<http://www.fda.gov/cber/gdlns/sarsbldgd.htm>. A similar action was
implemented by Health Canada several weeks ago upon the recognition
of the transmission chains of SARS in Ontario. The rationale for
excluding individuals for 2 weeks following possible exposure is
allowing for passage of the accepted incubation period for SARS,
which is currently described as 2-10 days. Waiting 28 days following
the diagnosis of SARS allows for termination of infection, so that
the virus would presumably no longer be present in blood of an
infected individual. Both of these time frames are based on
epidemiologic investigations and not on laboratory studies of large
numbers of cases. - Mod.MPP]

