[5]
Date: 18 Apr 2003
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: News briefs [edited]

[A] India from the India Express 18 Apr 2003
<http://www.indianexpress.com/full_story.php?content_id=22298>

One more patient "assumed to be normal" by the health authorities has
tested positive for SARS in the preliminary Polymerase Chain Reaction
(PCR) tests. The patient is a 42-year-old tourist from New Zealand
who landed at the Indira Gandhi International Airport, New Delhi,
from Bangkok at around 11 PM on Thursday night [17 Apr 2003]. He has
been admitted to the Ram Manohar Lohia hospital. According to
sources at the National Institute of Communicable Diseases, New
Delhi, genetic sequencing is being matched and the results will be
declared in the next 24 hours.

The New Zealander was moved to the hospital with symptoms such as
cough and breathlessness. The official version this evening was that
the patient was 'afebrile' with no symptoms. "His X-ray is normal and
he has no fever," they said. According to sources at the airport, the
patient had attracted attention of the doctors at the health
counters, as he showed breathlessness. According to the NICD, the
passenger had travelled to Australia, where he stayed in New Port
with his brother, who was suspected to be infected and had been
quarantined. He had also stayed in Bangkok for 13 hours before flying
to India.

[B] China - Beijing - reported on Time.com
<http://www.time.com/time/asia/news/daily/0,9754,444684,00.html>
and on CNN
<http://www.cnn.com/2003/WORLD/asiapcf/east/04/18/sars.china/index.html>

[Our thanks to Jack Steinmann <jsteinmann@CLYNCH.COM> for submitting
the Time.com report on this - Mod.MPP]

Both reports mentioned an intentional physical hiding of suspected
cases of SARS from the WHO teams during the visits of the teams to
the hospitals: "...hospital officials removed dozens of SARS patients
from their isolation wards and transferred them to locations where
they could not be observed by the inspectors" (from the Time.com
article).

The full reports of these allegations apparently made by physicians
working at the involved hospitals can be read at the above given URL
links.

--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[In the news brief section there is a report of another suspected
case in India, with mention that preliminary results of PCR testing
were positive. According to that report, the patient (an individual
from New Zealand) travelled from Bangkok, which to date has not been
reported as having areas of local transmission. We await further
information on this case, and possible exposure. It should be
mentioned that the PCR test is capable of producing not only false
negative results (negative when there is a real infection), but also
false positives (positive when the individual is not infected with
the virus). Therefore, a positive PCR at present does not "confirm"
that this is a case of SARS (see discussion in [4][A] related to
change in case definitions used by the USA for reporting).

The WHO is recommending -- and all countries to date have been
complying with -- the application of a case definition based on
clinical and epidemiologic criteria, and not based on results of
laboratory diagnostic testing, now that tests are available. Data
from laboratory testing are being collected and analyzed to better
define the sensitivity (ability to detect the virus when present,
resulting in a low false negative rate) and specificity (ability to
rule out the presence of the virus when not present, resulting in a
low false positive rate) of the tests currently available.

The reports on the possible "hiding" of SARS patients from the WHO
team involved in the inspections come on the eve of the Chinese
political leadership mandating that full international cooperation be
provided in the ongoing investigation and control measures related to
the SARS outbreak. This announcement was made by the Chinese
president (see SARS - worldwide (56): cases 20030418.0951), and
included full disclosure and reporting of all suspected and probable
cases to the Ministry of Health and from the Ministry of Health to
international organizations. The above newswires are very critical
and make serious allegations regarding intentional underreporting of
SARS cases. Confirmation might be expected soon, in the form of
marked increases in numbers of probable cases reported in a very
short time frame. In the absence of this, one must speculate that
these accusations were not based on fact. We await further
clarification. - Mod.MPP]
